# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apl-array
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] A mathematical notation for manipulating arrays was developed by Kenneth E.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Iverson, starting in 1957 at Harvard University.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] In 1960, he began work for IBM where he developed this notation with Adin Falkoff and published it in his book *A Programming Language* in 1962.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] This notation was used inside IBM for short research reports on computer systems, such as the Burroughs B5000 and its stack mechanism when stack machines versus register machines were being evaluated by IBM for upcoming computers.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Iverson also used his notation in a draft of the chapter *A Programming Language*, written for a book he was writing with Fred Brooks, *Automatic Data Processing*, which would be published in 1963.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] In 1979, Iverson received the Turing Award for his work on APL.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] As early as 1962, the first attempt to use the notation to describe a complete computer system happened after Falkoff discussed with William C.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Carter his work to standardize the instruction set for the machines that later became the IBM System/360 family.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] In 1963, Herbert Hellerman, working at the IBM Systems Research Institute, implemented a part of the notation on an IBM 1620 computer, and it was used by students in a special high school course on calculating transcendental functions by series summation.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Students tested their code in Hellerman's lab.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] This implementation of a part of the notation was called Personalized Array Translator (PAT).
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] In 1963, Falkoff, Iverson, and Edward H.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Sussenguth Jr., all working at IBM, used the notation for a formal description of the IBM System/360 series machine architecture and functionality, which resulted in a paper published in *IBM Systems Journal* in 1964.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] After this was published, the team turned their attention to an implementation of the notation on a computer system.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] One of the motivations for this focus of implementation was the interest of John L.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Lawrence who had new duties with Science Research Associates, an educational company bought by IBM in 1964.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Lawrence asked Iverson and his group to help use the language as a tool to develop and use computers in education.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Abrams of Stanford University joined the team at IBM Research, they continued their prior work on an implementation programmed in FORTRAN IV for a part of the notation which had been done for the IBM 7090 computer running on the IBSYS operating system.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] This work was finished in late 1965 and later named IVSYS (for Iverson system).
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] The basis of this implementation was described in detail by Abrams in a Stanford University Technical Report, "An Interpreter for Iverson Notation" in 1966.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] The academic aspect of this was formally supervised by Niklaus Wirth.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Like Hellerman's PAT system earlier, this implementation omitted the APL character set, but used special English reserved words for functions and operators.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] The system was later adapted for a time-sharing system and, by November 1966, it had been reprogrammed for the IBM System/360 Model 50 computer running in a time-sharing mode and was used internally at IBM.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] A key development in the ability to use APL effectively, before the wide use of cathode-ray tube (CRT) terminals, was the development of a special IBM Selectric typewriter interchangeable typing element with all the special APL characters on it.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] This was used on paper printing terminal workstations using the Selectric typewriter and typing element mechanism, such as the IBM 1050 and IBM 2741 terminal.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Keycaps could be placed over the normal keys to show which APL characters would be entered and typed when that key was struck.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] For the first time, a programmer could type in and see proper APL characters as used in Iverson's notation and not be forced to use awkward English keyword representations of them.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Falkoff and Iverson had the special APL Selectric typing elements, 987 and 988, designed in late 1964, although no APL computer system was available to use them.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Iverson cited Falkoff as the inspiration for the idea of using an IBM Selectric typing element for the APL character set.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Many APL symbols, even with the APL characters on the Selectric typing element, still had to be typed in by over-striking two extant element characters.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] An example is the *grade up* character, which had to be made from a *delta* (shift-H) and a *Sheffer stroke* (shift-M).
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] This was necessary because the APL character set was much larger than the 88 characters allowed on the typing element, even when letters were restricted to upper-case (capitals).
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] The Tektronix 4013 Computer Display Terminal is a Tektronix 4010 with both the APL and ASCII character sets.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] There is a rocker switch above the keys to select the character set.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] The first APL interactive login and creation of an APL workspace was in 1966 by Larry Breed using an IBM 1050 terminal at the IBM Mohansic Labs near Thomas J.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Watson Research Center, the home of APL, in Yorktown Heights, New York.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] IBM was chiefly responsible for introducing APL to the marketplace.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] The first publicly available version of APL was released in 1968 for the IBM 1130.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] IBM provided *APL\1130* for free but without liability or support.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] It would run in as little as 8k 16-bit words of memory, and used a dedicated 1 megabyte hard disk.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] APL gained its foothold on mainframe timesharing systems from the late 1960s through the early 1980s, in part because it would support multiple users on lower-specification systems that had no dynamic address translation hardware.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Additional improvements in performance for selected IBM System/370 mainframe systems included the *APL Assist Microcode* in which some support for APL execution was included in the processor's firmware, as distinct from being implemented entirely by higher-level software.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Somewhat later, as suitably performing hardware was finally growing available in the mid- to late-1980s, many users migrated their applications to the personal computer environment.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Early IBM APL interpreters for IBM 360 and IBM 370 hardware implemented their own multi-user management instead of relying on the host services, thus they were their own timesharing systems.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] First introduced for use at IBM in 1966, the *APL\360* system was a multi-user interpreter.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] The ability to programmatically communicate with the operating system for information and setting interpreter system variables was done through special privileged "I-beam" functions, using both monadic and dyadic operations.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] In 1973, IBM released *APL.SV*, which was a continuation of the same product, but which offered shared variables as a means to access facilities outside of the APL system, such as operating system files.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] In the mid-1970s, the IBM mainframe interpreter was even adapted for use on the IBM 5100 desktop computer, which had a small CRT and an APL keyboard, when most other small computers of the time only offered BASIC.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] In the 1980s, the *VSAPL* program product enjoyed wide use with Conversational Monitor System (CMS), Time Sharing Option (TSO), VSPC, MUSIC/SP, and CICS users.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Hagerty directed the implementation of the University of Maryland APL interpreter for the 1100 line of the Sperry UNIVAC 1100/2200 series mainframe computers.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] In 1974, student Alan Stebbens was assigned the task of implementing an internal function.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Xerox APL was available from June 1975 for Xerox 560 and Sigma 6, 7, and 9 mainframes running CP-V and for Honeywell CP-6.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] In the 1960s and 1970s, several timesharing firms arose that sold APL services using modified versions of the IBM APL\360 interpreter.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] In North America, the better-known ones were IP Sharp Associates, Scientific Time Sharing Corporation (STSC), Time Sharing Resources (TSR), and The Computer Company (TCC).
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] CompuServe also entered the market in 1978 with an APL Interpreter based on a modified version of Digital Equipment Corp and Carnegie Mellon's, which ran on DEC's KI and KL 36-bit machines.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] CompuServe's APL was available both to its commercial market and the consumer information service.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] With the advent first of less expensive mainframes such as the IBM 4300, and later the personal computer, by the mid-1980s, the timesharing industry was all but gone.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] APL interpreters were available from other mainframe and mini-computer manufacturers also, notably Burroughs, Control Data Corporation (CDC), Data General, Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC), Harris, Hewlett-Packard (HP), Siemens, Xerox and others.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Garth Foster of Syracuse University sponsored regular meetings of the APL implementers' community at Syracuse's Minnowbrook Conference Center in Blue Mountain Lake, New York.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] In later years, Eugene McDonnell organized similar meetings at the Asilomar Conference Grounds near Monterey, California, and at Pajaro Dunes near Watsonville, California.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] The SIGAPL special interest group of the Association for Computing Machinery continues to support the APL community.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] On microcomputers, which became available from the mid-1970s onwards, BASIC became the dominant programming language.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Nevertheless, some microcomputers provided APL instead – the first being the Intel 8008-based MCM/70 which was released in 1974 and which was primarily used in education.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Another machine of this time was the VideoBrain Family Computer, released in 1977, which was supplied with its dialect of APL called APL/S.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] The Commodore SuperPET, introduced in 1981, included an APL interpreter developed by the University of Waterloo.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] In 1976, Bill Gates claimed in his Open Letter to Hobbyists that Microsoft Corporation was implementing APL for the Intel 8080 and Motorola 6800 but had "very little incentive to make [it] available to hobbyists" because of software piracy.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Ken Iverson, no longer in control of the development of the APL language, left IBM and joined I.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Sharp Associates, where one of his major contributions was directing the evolution of Sharp APL to be more in accord with his vision.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] APL2 was first released for CMS and TSO in 1984.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] The APL2 Workstation edition (Windows, OS/2, AIX, Linux, and Solaris) followed later.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] As other vendors were busy developing APL interpreters for new hardware, notably Unix-based microcomputers, APL2 was almost always the standard chosen for new APL interpreter developments.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Even today, most APL vendors or their users cite APL2 compatibility as a selling point for those products.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] IBM cites its use for problem solving, system design, prototyping, engineering and scientific computations, expert systems, for teaching mathematics and other subjects, visualization and database access.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Various implementations of APL by APLX, Dyalog, et al., include extensions for object-oriented programming, support for .NET, XML-array conversion primitives, graphing, operating system interfaces, and lambda calculus expressions.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Freeware versions include GNU APL for Linux and NARS2000 for Windows (which also runs on Linux under Wine).
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Both of these are fairly complete versions of APL2 with various language extensions.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] APL has been criticized and praised for its choice of a unique character set.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] In the 1960s and 1970s, few terminal devices or even displays could reproduce the APL character set.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] The most popular ones employed the IBM Selectric print mechanism used with a special APL type element.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] One of the early APL line terminals (line-mode operation only, *not* full screen) was the Texas Instruments TI Model 745 (c.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] 1977) with the full APL character set which featured half and full duplex telecommunications modes, for interacting with an APL time-sharing service or remote mainframe to run a remote computer job, remote job entry (RJE).
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Over time, with the universal use of high-quality graphic displays, printing devices and Unicode support, the APL character font problem has largely been eliminated.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] However, entering APL characters requires the use of input method editors, keyboard mappings, virtual/on-screen APL symbol sets, or easy-reference printed keyboard cards which can frustrate beginners accustomed to other programming languages.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] With beginners who have no prior experience with other programming languages, a study involving high school students found that typing and using APL characters did not hinder the students in any measurable way.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] In defense of APL, it requires fewer characters to type, and keyboard mappings become memorized over time.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Special APL keyboards are also made and in use today, as are freely downloadable fonts for operating systems such as Microsoft Windows.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] The reported productivity gains assume that one spends enough time working in the language to make it worthwhile to memorize the symbols, their semantics, keyboard mappings, and many idioms for common tasks.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Unlike traditionally structured programming languages, APL code is typically structured as chains of monadic or dyadic functions, and operators acting on arrays.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] APL has many nonstandard *primitives* (functions and operators) that are indicated by a single symbol or a combination of a few symbols.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] All primitives are defined to have the same precedence, and always associate to the right.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Thus, APL is *read* or best understood from right-to-left.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] 1970 or so) had no programming loop control flow structures, such as `do` or `while` loops, and `if-then-else` constructs.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Instead, they used array operations, and use of structured programming constructs was often unneeded, since an operation could be performed on a full array in one statement.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] For example, the `iota` function (`ι`) can replace for-loop iteration: ιN when applied to a scalar positive integer yields a one-dimensional array (vector), 1 2 3 ...
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Later APL implementations generally include comprehensive control structures, so that data structure and program control flow can be clearly and cleanly separated.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] The APL environment is called a *workspace*.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] In a workspace the user can define programs and data, i.e., the data values exist also outside the programs, and the user can also manipulate the data without having to define a program.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] In the examples below, the APL interpreter first types six spaces before awaiting the user's input.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] The user can save the workspace with all values, programs, and execution status.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] APL uses a set of non-ASCII symbols, which are an extension of traditional arithmetic and algebraic notation.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Having single character names for single instruction, multiple data (SIMD) vector functions is one way that APL enables compact formulation of algorithms for data transformation such as computing Conway's Game of Life in one line of code.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] In nearly all versions of APL, it is theoretically possible to express any computable function in one expression, that is, in one line of code.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Due to the unusual character set, many programmers use special keyboards with APL keytops to write APL code.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Although there are various ways to write APL code using only ASCII characters, in practice it is almost never done.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] (This may be thought to support Iverson's thesis about notation as a tool of thought.) Most if not all modern implementations use standard keyboard layouts, with special mappings or input method editors to access non-ASCII characters.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Historically, the APL font has been distinctive, with uppercase italic alphabetic characters and upright numerals and symbols.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Most vendors continue to display the APL character set in a custom font.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Advocates of APL claim that the examples of so-called *write-only code* (badly written and almost incomprehensible code) are almost invariably examples of poor programming practice or novice mistakes, which can occur in any language.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Advocates also claim that they are far more productive with APL than with more conventional computer languages, and that working software can be implemented in far less time and with far fewer programmers than using other technology.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] They also may claim that because it is compact and terse, APL lends itself well to larger-scale software development and complexity, because the number of lines of code can be reduced greatly.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Many APL advocates and practitioners also view standard programming languages such as COBOL and Java as being comparatively tedious.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] APL is often found where time-to-market is important, such as with trading systems.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] APL makes a clear distinction between *functions* and *operators*.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Functions take arrays (variables or constants or expressions) as arguments, and return arrays as results.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Operators (similar to higher-order functions) take functions or arrays as arguments, and derive related functions.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] For example, the *sum* function is derived by applying the *reduction* operator to the *addition* function.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Applying the same reduction operator to the *maximum* function (which returns the larger of two numbers) derives a function which returns the largest of a group (vector) of numbers.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] In the J language, Iverson substituted the terms *verb* for *function* and *adverb* or *conjunction* for *operator*.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] APL also identifies those features built into the language, and represented by a symbol, or a fixed combination of symbols, as *primitives*.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Most primitives are either functions or operators.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Coding APL is largely a process of writing non-primitive functions and (in some versions of APL) operators.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] However a few primitives are considered to be neither functions nor operators, most noticeably assignment.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Some words used in APL literature have meanings that differ from those in both mathematics and the generality of computer science.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] APL has explicit representations of functions, operators, and syntax, thus providing a basis for the clear and explicit statement of extended facilities in the language, and tools to experiment on them.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] A design theme in APL is to define default actions in some cases that would produce syntax errors in most other programming languages.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] The 'Hello, world' string constant above displays, because display is the default action on any expression for which no action is specified explicitly (e.g. assignment, function parameter).
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Another example of this theme is that exponentiation in APL is written as `2*3`, which indicates raising 2 to the power 3 (this would be written as `2^3` or `2**3` in some languages, or relegated to a function call such as `pow(2, 3);` in others).
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Many languages use `*` to signify multiplication, as in `2*3`, but APL chooses to use `2×3`.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] However, if no base is specified (as with the statement `*3` in APL, or `^3` in other languages), most programming languages one would see this as a syntax error.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] APL, however, assumes the missing base to be the natural logarithm constant e, and interprets `*3` as `2.71828*3`.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Suppose that `X` is an array of numbers.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Reading *right-to-left*, `⍴X` gives the number of elements in X, and since `÷` is a dyadic operator, the term to its left is required as well.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] It is surrounded by parentheses since otherwise X would be taken (so that the summation would be of `X÷⍴X`—each element of X divided by the number of elements in X), and `+/X` gives the sum of the elements of X.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Naturally, one would define this expression as a function for repeated use rather than rewriting it each time.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] The above does a lot, concisely, although it may seem complex to a new APLer.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Since there is no function to the left of the left-most x to tell APL what to do with the result, it simply outputs it to the display (on a single line, separated by spaces) without needing any explicit instruction to do that.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] `?` also has a monadic equivalent called `roll`, which simply returns one random integer between 1 and its sole operand [to the right of it], inclusive.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Thus, a role-playing game program might use the expression `?20` to roll a twenty-sided die.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] The following expression finds all prime numbers from 1 to R.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] In both time and space, the calculation complexity is $O(R^{2})\,\!$ (in Big O notation).
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] (This assumes the APL origin is 1, i.e., indices start with 1.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] The following function "life", written in Dyalog APL, takes a Boolean matrix and calculates the new generation according to Conway's Game of Life.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] It demonstrates the power of APL to implement a complex algorithm in very little code, but understanding it requires some advanced knowledge of APL (as the same program would in many languages).
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] APL derives its name from the initials of Iverson's book *A Programming Language*, even though the book describes Iverson's mathematical notation, rather than the implemented programming language described in this article.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] The name is used only for actual implementations, starting with APL\360.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] There has always been cooperation between APL vendors, and joint conferences were held on a regular basis from 1969 until 2010.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] At such conferences, APL merchandise was often handed out, featuring APL motifs or collection of vendor logos.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Common were apples (as a pun on the similarity in pronunciation of *apple* and *APL*) and the code snippet `⍺*⎕` which are the symbols produced by the classic APL keyboard layout when holding the APL modifier key and typing "APL".
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Despite all these community efforts, no universal vendor-agnostic logo for the programming language emerged.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] APL is used for many purposes including financial and insurance applications, artificial intelligence, neural networks and robotics.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] It has been argued that APL is a calculation tool and not a programming language; its symbolic nature and array capabilities have made it popular with domain experts and data scientists who do not have or require the skills of a computer programmer.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] APL is well suited to image manipulation and computer animation, where graphic transformations can be encoded as matrix multiplications.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] One of the first commercial computer graphics houses, Digital Effects, produced an APL graphics product named *Visions*, which was used to create television commercials and animation for the 1982 film *Tron*.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Latterly, the Stormwind boating simulator uses APL to implement its core logic, its interfacing to the rendering pipeline middleware and a major part of its physics engine.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Today, APL remains in use in a wide range of commercial and scientific applications, asset management, health care, and DNA profiling.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] The first implementation of APL using recognizable APL symbols was APL\360 which ran on the IBM System/360, and was completed in November 1966 though at that time remained in use only within IBM.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] In 1973 its implementors, Larry Breed, Dick Lathwell and Roger Moore, were awarded the Grace Murray Hopper Award from the Association for Computing Machinery (ACM).
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] In 1975, the IBM 5100 microcomputer offered APL\360 as one of two built-in ROM-based interpreted languages for the computer, complete with a keyboard and display that supported all the special symbols used in the language.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Significant developments to APL\360 included CMS/APL, which made use of the virtual storage capabilities of CMS and APLSV, which introduced shared variables, system variables and system functions.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] It was subsequently ported to the IBM System/370 and VSPC platforms until its final release in 1983, after which it was replaced by APL2.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] In 1968, APL\1130 became the first publicly available APL system, created by IBM for the IBM 1130.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] It became the most popular IBM Type-III Library software that IBM released.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] APL*Plus and Sharp APL are versions of APL\360 with added business-oriented extensions such as data formatting and facilities to store APL arrays in external files.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] They were jointly developed by two companies, employing various members of the original IBM APL\360 development team.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Sharp Associates (IPSA), an APL\360 services company formed in 1964 by Ian Sharp, Roger Moore and others, and STSC, a time-sharing and consulting service company formed in 1969 by Lawrence Breed and others.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Together the two developed APL*Plus and thereafter continued to work together but develop APL separately as APL*Plus and Sharp APL.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] STSC ported APL*Plus to many platforms with versions being made for the VAX 11, PC and UNIX, whereas IPSA took a different approach to the arrival of the personal computer and made Sharp APL available on this platform using additional PC-XT/360 hardware.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] In 1993, Soliton Incorporated was formed to support Sharp APL and it developed Sharp APL into SAX (Sharp APL for Unix).
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] As of 2018, APL*Plus continues as APL2000 APL+Win.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] In 1985, Ian Sharp, and Dan Dyer of STSC, jointly received the Kenneth E.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Iverson Award for Outstanding Contribution to APL.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] APL2 was a significant re-implementation of APL by IBM which was developed from 1971 and first released in 1984.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] It provides many additions to the language, of which the most notable is nested (non-rectangular) array support.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] The entire APL2 Products and Services Team was awarded the Iverson Award in 2007.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] In 2021, IBM sold APL2 to Log-On Software, who develop and sell the product as *Log-On APL2*.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] In 1972, APLGOL was released as an experimental version of APL that added structured programming language constructs to the language framework.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] New statements were added for interstatement control, conditional statement execution, and statement structuring, as well as statements to clarify the intent of the algorithm.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] It was implemented for Hewlett-Packard in 1977.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Dyalog APL was first released by British company Dyalog Ltd. in 1983 and, as of 2018, is available for AIX, Linux (including on the Raspberry Pi), macOS and Microsoft Windows platforms.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] It is based on APL2, with extensions to support object-oriented programming, functional programming, and tacit programming.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Licences are free for personal/non-commercial use.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] In 1995, two of the development team – John Scholes and Peter Donnelly – were awarded the Iverson Award for their work on the interpreter.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Gitte Christensen and Morten Kromberg were joint recipients of the Iverson Award in 2016.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] NARS2000 is an open-source APL interpreter written by Bob Smith, a prominent APL developer and implementor from STSC in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] NARS2000 contains advanced features and new datatypes and runs natively on Microsoft Windows, and other platforms under Wine.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] It is named after a development tool from the 1980s, NARS (Nested Arrays Research System).
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] APLX is a cross-platform dialect of APL, based on APL2 and with several extensions, which was first released by British company MicroAPL in 2002.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Although no longer in development or on commercial sale it is now available free of charge from Dyalog.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] York APL was developed at the York University, Ontario around 1968, running on IBM 360 mainframes.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] One notable difference between it and APL\360 was that it defined the "shape" (ρ) of a scalar as 1 whereas APL\360 defined it as the more mathematically correct 0 — this made it easier to write functions that acted the same with scalars and vectors.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] GNU APL is a free implementation of Extended APL as specified in ISO/IEC 13751:2001 and is thus an implementation of APL2.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] It runs on Linux, macOS, several BSD dialects, and on Windows (either using Cygwin for full support of all its system functions or as a native 64-bit Windows binary with some of its system functions missing).
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] GNU APL uses Unicode internally and can be scripted.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Richard Stallman, founder of the GNU Project, was an early adopter of APL, using it to write a text editor as a high school student in the summer of 1969.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] APL is traditionally an interpreted language, having language characteristics such as weak variable typing not well suited to compilation.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Most APL interpreters support idiom recognition and evaluate common idioms as single operations.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] For example, by evaluating the idiom `BV/⍳⍴A` as a single operation (where `BV` is a Boolean vector and `A` is an array), the creation of two intermediate arrays is avoided.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Weak typing in APL means that a name may reference an array (of any datatype), a function or an operator.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] In general, the interpreter cannot know in advance which form it will be and must therefore perform analysis, syntax checking etc. at run-time.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] However, in certain circumstances, it is possible to deduce in advance what type a name is expected to reference and then generate bytecode which can be executed with reduced run-time overhead.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] This bytecode can also be optimised using compilation techniques such as constant folding or common subexpression elimination.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] The interpreter will execute the bytecode when present and when any assumptions which have been made are met.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Dyalog APL includes support for optimised bytecode.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] Compilation of APL has been the subject of research and experiment since the language first became available; the first compiler is considered to be the Burroughs APL-700 which was released around 1971.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] In order to be able to compile APL, language limitations have to be imposed.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] APEX is a research APL compiler which was written by Robert Bernecky and is available under the GNU General Public License.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] APL has been standardized by the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) working group X3J10 and International Organization for Standardization (ISO) and International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), ISO/IEC Joint Technical Committee 1 Subcommittee 22 Working Group 3.
[src:apl-array/apl-programming-language] The Core APL language is specified in ISO 8485:1989, and the Extended APL language is specified in ISO/IEC 13751:2001.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] In computer science, **array programming** refers to solutions that allow the application of operations to an entire set of values at once.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] Such solutions are commonly used in scientific and engineering settings.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] Modern programming languages that support array programming (also known as vector or multidimensional languages) have been engineered specifically to generalize operations on scalars to apply transparently to vectors, matrices, and higher-dimensional arrays.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] These include APL, J, Fortran, MATLAB, Analytica, Octave, PL/I, R, Cilk Plus, Julia, Perl Data Language (PDL) and Raku.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] In these languages, an operation that operates on entire arrays can be called a *vectorized* operation, regardless of whether it is executed on a vector processor, which implements vector instructions.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] Array programming primitives concisely express broad ideas about data manipulation.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] The level of concision can be dramatic in certain cases: it is not uncommon to find array programming language one-liners that require several pages of object-oriented code.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] The fundamental idea behind array programming is that operations apply at once to an entire set of values.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] This makes it a high-level programming model as it allows the programmer to think and operate on whole aggregates of data, without having to resort to explicit loops of individual scalar operations.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] The basis behind array programming and thinking is to find and exploit the properties of data where individual elements are similar or adjacent.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] Unlike object orientation which implicitly breaks down data to its constituent parts (or scalar quantities), array orientation looks to group data and apply a uniform handling.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] Function rank is an important concept to array programming languages in general, by analogy to tensor rank in mathematics: functions that operate on data may be classified by the number of dimensions they act on.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] Ordinary multiplication, for example, is a scalar ranked function because it operates on zero-dimensional data (individual numbers).
[src:apl-array/array-programming] The cross product operation is an example of a vector rank function because it operates on vectors, not scalars.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] Matrix multiplication is an example of a 2-rank function, because it operates on 2-dimensional objects (matrices).
[src:apl-array/array-programming] Collapse operators reduce the dimensionality of an input data array by one or more dimensions.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] For example, summing over elements collapses the input array by 1 dimension.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] Array programming is very well suited to implicit parallelization; a topic of much research nowadays.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] Further, Intel and compatible CPUs developed and produced after 1997 contained various instruction set extensions, starting from MMX and continuing through SSSE3 and 3DNow!, which include rudimentary SIMD array capabilities.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] This has continued into the 2020s with instruction sets such as AVX-512, making modern CPUs sophisticated vector processors.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] Array processing is distinct from parallel processing in that one physical processor performs operations on a group of items simultaneously while parallel processing aims to split a larger problem into smaller ones (MIMD) to be solved piecemeal by numerous processors.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] Processors with multiple cores and GPUs with thousands of general computing cores are common as of 2023.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] The canonical examples of array programming languages are Fortran, APL, and J.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] Others include: A+, Analytica, Chapel, IDL, Julia, K, Klong, Q, MATLAB, GNU Octave, Scilab, FreeMat, Perl Data Language (PDL), R, Raku, S-Lang, SAC, Nial, ZPL, Futhark, and TI-BASIC.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] In scalar languages such as C and Pascal, operations apply only to single values, so *a*+*b* expresses the addition of two numbers.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] In such languages, adding one array to another requires indexing and looping, the coding of which is tedious.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] Some C compilers like GCC at some optimization levels detect and vectorize sections of code that its heuristics determine would benefit from it.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] Another approach is given by the OpenMP API, which allows one to parallelize applicable sections of code by taking advantage of multiple CPU cores.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] In array languages, operations are generalized to apply to both scalars and arrays.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] Thus, *a*+*b* expresses the sum of two scalars if *a* and *b* are scalars, or the sum of two arrays if they are arrays.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] An array language simplifies programming but possibly at a cost known as the *abstraction penalty*.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] Because the additions are performed in isolation from the rest of the coding, they may not produce the optimally most efficient code.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] The previous C code would become the following in the Ada language, which supports array-programming syntax.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] APL uses single character Unicode symbols with no syntactic sugar.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] This operation works on arrays of any rank (including rank 0), and on a scalar and an array.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] Analytica provides the same economy of expression as Ada.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] Dartmouth BASIC had MAT statements for matrix and array manipulation in its third edition (1966).
[src:apl-array/array-programming] Stata's matrix programming language Mata supports array programming.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] Below, we illustrate addition, multiplication, addition of a matrix and a scalar, element by element multiplication, subscripting, and one of Mata's many inverse matrix functions.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] The implementation in MATLAB allows the same economy allowed by using the Fortran language.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] Both MATLAB and GNU Octave natively support linear algebra operations such as matrix multiplication, matrix inversion, and the numerical solution of system of linear equations, even using the Moore–Penrose pseudoinverse.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] The Nial example of the inner product of two arrays can be implemented using the native matrix multiplication operator.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] If `a` is a row vector of size [1 n] and `b` is a corresponding column vector of size [n 1].
[src:apl-array/array-programming] The rasdaman query language is a database-oriented array-programming language.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] The R language supports array paradigm by default.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] Raku supports the array paradigm via its Metaoperators.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] The following example demonstrates the addition of arrays @a and @b using the Hyper-operator in conjunction with the plus operator.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] The matrix left-division operator concisely expresses some semantic properties of matrices.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] As in the scalar equivalent, if the (determinant of the) coefficient (matrix) `A` is not null then it is possible to solve the (vectorial) equation `A * x = b` by left-multiplying both sides by the inverse of `A`: `A−1` (in both MATLAB and GNU Octave languages: `A^-1`).
[src:apl-array/array-programming] where `==` is the equivalence relational operator.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] The previous statements are also valid MATLAB expressions if the third one is executed before the others (numerical comparisons may be false because of round-off errors).
[src:apl-array/array-programming] However, these solutions are neither the most concise ones (e.g. still remains the need to notationally differentiate overdetermined systems) nor the most computationally efficient.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] The latter point is easy to understand when considering again the scalar equivalent `a * x = b`, for which the solution `x = a^-1 * b` would require two operations instead of the more efficient `x = b / a`.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] This is not only an example of terse array programming from the coding point of view but also from the computational efficiency perspective, which in several array programming languages benefits from quite efficient linear algebra libraries such as ATLAS or LAPACK.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] The use of specialized and efficient libraries to provide more terse abstractions is also common in other programming languages.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] In C++ several linear algebra libraries exploit the language's ability to overload operators.
[src:apl-array/array-programming] In some cases a very terse abstraction in those languages is explicitly influenced by the array programming paradigm, as the NumPy extension library to Python, Armadillo and Blitz++ libraries do.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] The **J** programming language, developed in the early 1990s by Kenneth E.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] Iverson and Roger Hui, is an array programming language based primarily on APL (also by Iverson).
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] To avoid repeating the APL special-character problem, J uses only the basic ASCII character set, resorting to the use of the dot and colon as *inflections* to form short words similar to *digraphs*.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] Most such *primary* (or *primitive*) J words serve as mathematical symbols, with the dot or colon extending the meaning of the basic characters available.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] Also, many characters which in other languages often must be paired (such as [] {} "" `` or `<>`) are treated by J as stand-alone words or, when inflected, as single-character roots of multi-character words.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] J is a very terse array programming language, and is most suited to mathematical and statistical programming, especially when performing operations on matrices.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] It has also been used in extreme programming and network performance analysis.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] Like John Backus's languages FP and FL, J supports function-level programming via its *tacit programming* features.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] Unlike most languages that support object-oriented programming, J's flexible hierarchical namespace scheme (where every name exists in a specific *locale*) can be effectively used as a framework for both class-based and prototype-based object-oriented programming.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] Since March 2011, J is free and open-source software under the GNU General Public License version 3 (GPLv3).
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] One may also purchase source under a negotiated license.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] J permits point-free style and function composition.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] Thus, its programs can be very terse and are considered difficult to read by some programmers.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] This implementation of hello world reflects the traditional use of J – programs are entered into a J interpreter session, and the results of expressions are displayed.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] It's also possible to arrange for J scripts to be executed as standalone programs.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] (Note that current j implementations install either `jconsole` or (because jconsole is used by java), `ijconsole` and likely install this to /usr/bin or some other directory (perhaps the Application directory on macOS).
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] Historically, APL used `/` to indicate the fold, so `+/1 2 3` was equivalent to `1+2+3`.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] Meanwhile, division was represented with the mathematical division symbol (`÷`).
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] Because ASCII does not include a division symbol *per se*, J uses % to represent division, as a visual approximation or reminder.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] Above, *avg* is defined using a train of three verbs (`+/`, `%`, and `#`) termed a *fork*.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] Specifically, `(V0 V1 V2) Ny` is the same as `(V0(Ny)) V1 (V2(Ny))` which shows some of the power of J.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] The following is an implementation of quicksort demonstrating tacit programming.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] The latter involves composing functions together and not referring explicitly to any variables.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] J's support for *forks* and *hooks* dictates rules on how arguments applied to this function will be applied to its component functions.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] Sorting in J is usually accomplished using the built-in (primitive) verbs `/:` (sort up) and `\:` (sort down).
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] User-defined sorts such as quicksort, above, typically are for illustration only.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] A program or routine – something that takes data as input and produces data as output – is called a *verb*.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] User programs can be named and used wherever primitives are allowed.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] The power of J comes largely from its *modifiers*: symbols that take nouns **and verbs** as operands and apply the operands in a specified way.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] For example, the modifier / takes one operand, a verb to its left, and produces a verb that applies that verb between each item of its argument.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] J has roughly two dozen of these modifiers.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] All of them can apply to any verb, even a user-written verb, and users may write their own modifiers.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] some of the modifiers control the order in which components are executed, allowing modifiers to be combined in any order to produce the unlimited variety of operations needed for practical programming.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] Of these, numeric has the most variants.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] For example, `1 0 1 0 1 1 0 0` is a list of eight bits.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] Syntactically, the J parser treats that as one word.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] (The space character is recognized as a word-forming character between what would otherwise be numeric words.) Lists of arbitrary length are supported.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] Further, J supports all the usual binary operations on these lists, such as *and*, *or*, *exclusive or*, *rotate*, *shift*, *not*, etc.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] J also supports higher order arrays of bits.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] They can be formed into two-dimensional, three-dimensional, etc. arrays.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] The above operations perform equally well on these arrays.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] As with bits, these can be formed into lists or arbitrarily dimensioned arrays.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] As with bits, operations are performed on all numbers in an array.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] Lists of bits can be converted to integer using the `#.` verb.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] Integers can be converted to lists of bits using the `#:` verb.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] (When parsing J, `.` (period) and `:` (colon) are word-forming characters.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] J also supports the literal (character) type.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] Literals are enclosed in quotes, for example, `'a'` or `'b'`.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] Lists of literals are also supported using the usual convention of putting multiple characters in quotes, such as `'abcdefg'`.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] Typically, individual literals are 8-bits wide (ASCII), but J also supports other literals (Unicode).
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] Numeric and Boolean operations are not supported on literals, but collection-oriented operations (such as rotate) are supported.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] Typically, data is put in a box using the `<` operation (with no left argument; if there's a left argument, this would be the *less than* operation).
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] This is analogous to C's `&` operation (with no left argument).
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] However, where the result of C's `&` has reference semantics, the result of J's `<` has value semantics.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] In other words, `<` is a function and it produces a result.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] The result has 0 dimensions, regardless of the structure of the contained data.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] From the viewpoint of a J programmer, `<` *puts the data into a box* and allows working with an array of boxes (it can be assembled with other boxes or more copies can be made of the box).
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] The only collection type offered by J is the arbitrarily dimensioned array.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] Most algorithms can be expressed very concisely using operations on these arrays.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] J's arrays are homogeneously typed, for example the list `1 2 3` is a list of integers despite `1` being a bit.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] For the most part, these sorts of type issues are transparent to programmers.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] Only certain specialized operations reveal differences in type.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] For example, the list `1.0 0.0 1.0 0.0` would be treated exactly the same, by most operations, as the list `1 0 1 0`.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] J also supports sparse numeric arrays where non-zero values are stored with their indices.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] This is an efficient mechanism where relatively few values are non-zero.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] J also supports objects and classes, but these are an artifact of the way things are named, and are not data types.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] Instead, boxed literals are used to refer to objects (and classes).
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] J data has value semantics, but objects and classes need reference semantics.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] Another pseudo-type—associated with name, rather than value—is the memory mapped file.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] J has the usual facilities for stopping on error or at specified places within verbs.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] It also has a unique visual debugger, called *Dissect*, that gives a 2-D interactive display of the execution of a single J sentence.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] Because a single sentence of J performs as much computation as an entire subroutine in lower-level languages, the visual display is quite helpful.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] J's documentation includes a dictionary, with words in J identified as nouns, verbs, modifiers, and so on.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] Primary words are listed in the vocabulary, in which their respective parts of speech are indicated using markup.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] Note that verbs have two forms: monadic (arguments only on the right) and dyadic (arguments on the left and on the right).
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] For example, in '`-1`' the hyphen is a monadic verb, and in '`3-2`' the hyphen is a dyadic verb.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] The monadic definition is mostly independent of the dyadic definition, regardless of whether the verb is a primitive verb or a derived verb.
[src:apl-array/j-programming-language] J provides control structures similar to other procedural languages.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] Before developing K, Arthur Whitney had worked extensively with APL, first at I.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] Sharp Associates alongside Ken Iverson and Roger Hui, and later at Morgan Stanley developing financial applications.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] At Morgan Stanley, Whitney helped to develop A+, a variant of APL, to facilitate migrating APL applications from IBM mainframe computers to a network of Sun workstations.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] A+ had a smaller set of primitive functions and was designed for speed and to handle large sets of time series data.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] In 1993, Whitney left Morgan Stanley and developed the first version of the K language.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] At the same time he formed KX Systems to commercialize the product and signed an exclusive contract with Union Bank of Switzerland (UBS).
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] For the next four years he developed various financial and trading applications using K for UBS.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] The contract ended in 1997 when UBS merged with Swiss Bank.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] In 1998, KX Systems released kdb+, a database built on K. kdb was an in-memory, column-oriented database and included ksql, a query language with an SQL-like syntax.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] Whitney released a derivative of K called Shakti in 2018.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] They are both interpreted, interactive languages noted for concise and expressive syntax.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] They have simple rules of precedence based on right to left evaluation.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] The languages contain a rich set of primitive functions designed for processing arrays.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] These primitive functions include mathematical operations that work on arrays as whole data objects, and array operations, such as sorting or reversing the order of an array.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] Also, the language contains special operators that combine with primitive functions to perform types of iteration and recursion.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] Therefore, complex and extended transformations of a dataset can be expressed as a chain of sub-expressions, with each link performing a segment of the calculation and passing the results to the next link in the chain.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] Like APL, the primitive functions and operators are represented by single or double characters; however, unlike APL, K restricts itself to the ASCII character set (as does another APL variant, J).
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] To allow for this, the set of primitive functions for K is smaller and heavily overloaded, with each of the ASCII symbols representing two or more distinct functions or operations.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] In a given expression, the actual function referenced is determined by the context.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] Therefore, K expressions can be opaque and difficult to parse for humans.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] Reading from right to left the first `!` is modulo division that is performed on 7 and 4 resulting in 3.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] The next `!` is enumeration and lists the integers less than 3, resulting in the list 0 1 2.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] The final `!` is rotation where the list on the right is rotated two times to the left producing the final result of 2 0 1.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] The second core distinction of K is that functions are first-class objects, a concept borrowed from Scheme.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] First-class functions can be used in the same contexts where a data value can be used.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] Functions can be specified as anonymous expressions and used directly with other expressions.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] Function expressions are specified in K using curly brackets.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] In K, named functions are simply function expressions stored to a variable in the same way any data value is stored to a variable.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] Functions can be passed as an argument to another function or returned as a result from a function.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] K is an interpreted language where every statement is evaluated and its results displayed immediately.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] Literal expressions such as strings evaluate to themselves.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] 2. > returns the indices that would sort a list of values in descending order.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] 3. @ uses the integer values on the right to index into the original list of strings.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] 2_ drops the first two elements of the enumeration (0 and 1).
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] 3. x!/: performs modulo division between the original integer and each value in the truncated list.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] 4. &/ find the minimum value of the list of modulo result.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] If x is not prime then one of the values returned by the modulo operation will be 0 and consequently the minimal value of the list.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] If x is prime then the minimal value will be 1, because x mod 2 is 1 for any prime greater than 2.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] ' apply each value of the enumeration to the prime number function on the left.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] 3. & return the indices of the list where the value is 1.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] K is the foundation for a family of financial products.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] Kdb+ is an in-memory, column-based database with much of the same functions of a relational database management system.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] The database supports SQL, SQL-92 and ksql, a query language with a syntax similar to SQL and designed for column based queries and array analysis.
[src:apl-array/k-programming-language] Kdb+ is available for several operating systems, including Solaris, Linux, macOS, and Windows (32-bit or 64-bit).
